  <!-- S7 WHY TRUST US (11A author card) -->
  <section id="trust">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Why This Comparison Isn't Symmetric — and Who's Telling You</h2>
    <div class="author-card">
      <img class="ac-banner" src="/Mark-with-our-grey-congo-parrot-pair-and-our-amazon-parrot.webp" srcset="/Mark-with-our-grey-congo-parrot-pair-and-our-amazon-parrot-760.webp 760w, /Mark-with-our-grey-congo-parrot-pair-and-our-amazon-parrot.webp 800w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 480px" width="800" height="600" alt="Mark at the C.A.Gs aviary in Midland, TX holding our Congo African Greys beside our green Amazon parrot, the two genera side by side" loading="lazy">
      <div class="ac-row">
        <img class="ac-avatar" src="/birds/bery/bery-grey-african-parrot-for-sale.webp" width="128" height="96" alt="Bery, a hand-raised Congo African Grey at the C.A.Gs aviary in Midland, TX" loading="lazy">
        <div><h3 class="ac-name">Mark &amp; Teri Benjamin</h3><p class="ac-sub">Hand-raising African Greys in Midland, Texas since 2014</p>
          <p class="ac-badges"><span>USDA-licensed breeders</span><span>CITES-documented</span><span>DNA sexed</span><span>PCR disease-screened</span></p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Here's the thing most comparisons hide: this matchup is lopsided by nature. "African Grey" is essentially two birds — the Congo and the Timneh. "Amazon" is a genus of more than thirty species that range from the gentle Red-Lored to the operatic, hormonally intense Double-Yellow-Head. Comparing a Grey to "an Amazon" is like comparing a specific dog to "a hound" — you have to name which one. That asymmetry is the whole reason we built the species section below, and it's why a single blanket "Amazons are…" sentence is almost always wrong.</p>
    <p>We're Mark and Teri Benjamin, hatching and hand-feeding African Greys at C.A.Gs since 2014, and "should I get an Amazon instead?" is a question we answer most weeks. Our Grey observations come straight from the nursery; our Amazon observations come from the owners, rescues and avian vets we've traded notes with for years. So here's the line no advertisement volunteers: a good Amazon out-sings any Grey we've raised, and it will charm your visitors in a way our one-person Greys simply won't.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why We Put Health Paperwork Above First Impressions</h3>
    <p>With a bird that may share your home for half a century, the sticker price is trivial next to the decades of care behind it — so we front-load the documentation that protects those decades. Each Grey ships with PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus PCR results, a DNA sexing certificate, an avian-vet health certificate, a hatch record and closed band, and the CITES Appendix I papers proving captive breeding on US soil. Our <a href="/african-grey-parrot-health-guarantee/">health guarantee page</a> commits the entire stack to writing.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-health-documentation-flat-lay.webp" srcset="/african-grey-health-documentation-flat-lay-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-health-documentation-flat-lay.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Flat-lay of a captive-bred African Grey's paperwork: DNA sexing certificate, PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus PCR results, hatch certificate and CITES documents" loading="lazy">
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S8 AFRICAN GREY DEEP DIVE -->
  <section id="grey">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Why Does the African Grey Out-Talk Most Amazons?</h2>
    <p>Beside a vivid green Amazon, the Grey looks understated — silver body, fine scalloping, a dark beak, and the Congo's one flash of colour in that bright red tail. The showmanship is all on the Amazon's side. What the Grey brings instead is the mind that landed the species in cognition research: words used in context, puzzles worked through, a quiet intelligence rather than a loud one. Buyers weighing "are African Greys good pets?" against an Amazon are really weighing substance against spectacle. The chicks weaning in our nursery now sit on our <a href="/congo-african-grey-for-sale/">Congo Grey</a> and <a href="/timneh-african-grey-for-sale/">Timneh Grey</a> pages.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">African Grey Size and Lifespan, Set Beside an Amazon</h3>
    <p>Unlike the Grey-versus-macaw mismatch, this one is a fair fight on size. A Congo tips the scale at 400–600 grams across 12–14 inches, the Timneh a notch below — right in the Amazon band, heftier than a pocket White-Fronted and just shy of a Double-Yellow-Head. Cage footprints are comparable, so square footage won't decide it. Longevity won't either: budget 40–60 years for a Grey and up to 70 for an Amazon. Whichever you pick, you're signing up for a companion that may see your children into adulthood.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Does a Grey's Temperament Read Next to an Amazon's?</h3>
    <p>Introverted, and intensely observant. Rearrange the living room and a Grey notices before you've finished; that same radar is why it needs a stimulating home and why it reads as "sensitive." An Amazon fills a room — struts, sings, works the crowd — while the Grey studies the room from the edge of it. Think of the Amazon as the extrovert at the party and the Grey as the one quietly running the household. Both are devoted; only one performs the devotion.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Can a Grey Live Where an Amazon Can't — a Small, Quiet Home?</h4>
    <p>Better than almost any Amazon. A Grey's default soundtrack is whistles, muttered words and a pitch-perfect impression of your microwave, concentrated into short morning and evening bursts — livable through a shared wall. An Amazon runs a longer, louder programme all day, and the yellow-headed singers carry furthest of all. You'll never silence a Grey (nor should you), but you can house one where a full-voiced Amazon would cost you the lease.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Does a Grey Bond as Readily With a Whole Family?</h4>
    <p>No — and naming that honestly is half the choice. A Grey usually appoints one person after a slow, private audition, then treats the rest of the household as trusted staff. Owners on <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/parrots/comments/1njxqge/african_greys_vs_amazons/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the r/parrots "African Grey's VS Amazons" thread ↗</a> describe exactly that ("bonded to me — my little shadow"), and it matches our nursery. An Amazon spreads its affection more freely across a family. Want a bird everyone can handle? Lean Amazon. Want one heart wholly yours? That's the Grey.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">A Grey's First Week: Reconnaissance, Not Sulking</h5>
    <p>Families sometimes phone us on day three worried their new Grey is "depressed." It isn't — it's running reconnaissance. A settling Grey perches low, watches more than it moves, and often waits for an empty room before it eats. That caution is a healthy bird taking the measure of its new world, and it lifts as the second week arrives and the personality steps forward. An Amazon typically bounces back louder and faster; a Grey earns its confidence slowly, then keeps it for decades.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: the day Maxy turned words into tools</h6>
    <p>Maxy, the talking Congo in our homepage clip, learned the way Greys tend to — by latching onto whatever word got him a result. "Teri" came first because it summoned someone; "bye bye" and "come here please" followed once he'd clocked that words move humans around. That is language as a tool, not a party trick, and it's the exact faculty an Amazon's singing never touches. An Amazon will out-perform Maxy on any melody; Maxy will out-reason it every time.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Health Screens Come Standard on a C.A.Gs Grey?</h3>
    <p>A Grey's risk profile is metabolic and viral where an Amazon's is dietary and hormonal, so the screening we prioritise differs from what an Amazon keeper watches for. Calcium comes first: Greys metabolise it atypically, and <a href="https://lafeber.com/vet/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lafeber's veterinary library ↗</a> lists hypocalcemia as a well-documented, species-specific danger — which is why UV-B lighting and a calcium-aware diet are in our care sheet from day one. Feather-destructive behaviour is the second watch-item. The Amazon's own weak spots get their own section below; on both sides, none of this is destiny, and all of it is why our buyer questions run as long as our paperwork.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">The Grey's Metabolic Weak Spots: Calcium and Feathers</h4>
    <p>Low blood calcium shows up as trembling or weakness and, untreated, as seizures — largely preventable with pellets, calcium-rich vegetables and real UV-B exposure so the bird can actually use that calcium. Plucking is usually boredom wearing a medical disguise: give a Grey genuine foraging work and the feathers generally stay put. The plain-language write-ups at <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/african-grey-parrots-general" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VCA Animal Hospitals ↗</a> cover both, and our diet-and-lighting plan ships with every bird on paper.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">What Our PCR Panel Rules Out Before a Grey Ships</h5>
    <p>Psittacine Beak and Feather Disease and Avian Polyomavirus are the two viruses that quietly convert a "bargain" parrot into a heartbreak — and they don't discriminate between a Grey and an Amazon. Every Grey we place carries an individual PCR result for both, a real lab report on that specific bird rather than a soothing line in an ad. Ask any seller of either species for the same panel; if it doesn't exist, neither does your safety margin.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: the World Parrot Trust species profile</h6>
    <p>These species-level points track the <a href="https://www.parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">World Parrot Trust profile of <em>Psittacus erithacus</em> ↗</a> — the same organisation whose trade work helped end the wild-capture era that once shadowed Greys and Amazons alike.</p>
  </section>

