  <!-- S9 AMAZON DEEP DIVE -->
  <section id="amazon">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Are Amazon Parrots Really Like to Live With?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/yellow-shouldered-amazon-pair.webp" srcset="/yellow-shouldered-amazon-pair-760.webp 760w, /yellow-shouldered-amazon-pair.webp 640w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="640" height="480" style="object-position:center 40%" alt="A pair of green Yellow-Shouldered Amazons, showing the extroverted, confident temperament that sets Amazons apart from a reserved African Grey" loading="lazy">
    <p>Amazons are the Americas' green extroverts, and sharing a home with one feels nothing like sharing one with a Grey. The Grey wins you with its mind; the Amazon wins you with sheer personality — confidence, showmanship, singing, and a swagger owners affectionately call "spicy." One keeper of both on <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/parrots/comments/1njxqge/african_greys_vs_amazons/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">the r/parrots comparison thread ↗</a> put it plainly: the grey is the shy shadow, the Amazon is the one that "would fall for most people who came over." The catch is the one this whole page keeps returning to — "Amazon" is thirty-plus species, and they are not interchangeable.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Are Amazon Parrots Cuddly, or Just Confident?</h3>
    <p>Mostly confident rather than cuddly. As one owner on the same thread warned, "I would definitely not describe most amazons as 'cuddly' — head scritches are tolerated, and beak kisses are allowed," but many Amazons prefer to be near you and performing rather than tucked under your chin. They're sociable and bold, often warming to a whole household faster than a Grey does. If you picture a bird that greets your guests and sings on the windowsill, that's the Amazon; if you picture a quiet one-person shadow, that's the Grey.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Loud and How "Spicy" Is an Amazon?</h3>
    <p>Loud, and seasonally spicy. Amazons project across the whole day, and the yellow-headed species are famous for volume that carries. "Spicy" is the community's word for the confident, sometimes-nippy streak that intensifies with hormones — an Orange-Winged owner described an Amazon that would "divebomb and attack women on sight" in breeding season. That's the extreme, not the norm, but it points at the Amazon's real cost: not neediness like a cockatoo, but the hormonal-maturity swing covered in its own section below.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Why Are Amazons Prone to Obesity?</h4>
    <p>Because they love a rich diet and, in many homes, get one. Amazons are built to work for their food and, given a seed-heavy bowl and a quiet cage, they gain weight and develop fatty liver disease at rates that worry avian vets. It's the Amazon's single most preventable health problem, and it's the mirror image of the Grey's calcium issue — a species-specific weak spot that good husbandry manages. A pellet-forward diet and real out-of-cage exercise keep it in check.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Are Amazons Smart Like Greys?</h4>
    <p>Bright and shrewd, yes — but their genius is social and musical rather than the Grey's contextual language. Amazons read a room, manipulate a household, and learn songs with a melodic accuracy no Grey matches. They can talk, and the top species talk well, but the science that made "parrot intelligence" a field was done with Greys, not Amazons. The practical read: an Amazon out-charms a Grey; a Grey out-reasons an Amazon.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Amazon's Best Trick: Singing</h5>
    <p>If a Grey's headline talent is contextual talking, an Amazon's is song. The Double-Yellow-Head and Yellow-Nape are called "opera singers" for good reason — they belt melodies with a prosody and volume a Grey's whistles never reach. Owners who love Amazons often love them for exactly this. It's the clearest single reason the Amazon isn't simply "a worse talking bird," and why the honest framing is talk-versus-sing, not better-versus-worse.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: why we still raise Greys, not Amazons</h6>
    <p>We're asked often why we don't add Amazons to the aviary. The honest answer: the hormonal-maturity swing in the yellow-headed species is a genuine welfare and rehoming risk we'd rather not sell into, and our whole model — DNA sexing, PCR screening, one-person-friendly hand-raising — is tuned to Greys. We'll happily point an Amazon-set buyer to a reputable Amazon breeder. What we won't do is pretend our Grey is an Amazon, or vice versa.</p>
  </section>

