    <p>Across all six, the pattern shifts as you move down the list: the easygoing Red-Lored demands the least and the yellow-headed singers the most, while the Grey stands off to one side as the quieter, dustier, more contextual talker. Pick the wrong Amazon for your household and you've made a harder choice than picking between "an Amazon" and a Grey ever was — which is exactly why naming the species first matters.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S11 TALKING vs SINGING -->
  <section id="talking">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Do Greys Talk Better While Amazons Sing Better?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-talking-vs-amazon-singing.webp" srcset="/african-grey-talking-vs-amazon-singing-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-talking-vs-amazon-singing.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="African grey talking vs amazon singing: the Grey leads on vocabulary and context, the Amazon leads on melody and volume" loading="lazy">
    <p>Broadly, yes — and it's the single most useful way to frame this choice. <strong>The Grey takes vocabulary and context; the Amazon takes melody and volume.</strong> A Grey can hold 200 to 1,000-plus words, articulate them crisply, and — the decisive part — apply them in context. The best Amazons — the Yellow-Naped and Double-Yellow-Headed — talk well too, but their headline gift is song, belted with a prosody a Grey never reaches. Owners of both say it cleanly: the grey is "much more vocal" with words, the Amazon is "the best singer out of all parrots."</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Vocabulary vs Comprehension: Where the Grey Pulls Ahead</h3>
    <p>Word count is only half the story; understanding is the rest. Over three decades, Dr. Irene Pepperberg's African Grey, Alex, learned to name colours, shapes and numbers and to answer questions he'd never been drilled on — proof of language with meaning behind it, not mimicry. Amazons mimic well and read a room shrewdly, yet that particular ceiling — words with comprehension — belongs to the Grey. Our <a href="/blog/african-grey-parrot-talking-ability/">African Grey talking-ability guide</a> sets realistic month-by-month expectations.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">Can Amazons Talk Well?</h4>
    <p>Yes — the top species genuinely can. A Yellow-Nape or Double-Yellow-Head can build a real vocabulary and deliver it with theatrical flair, and many owners rate them the best-talking Amazons. What they add is song and volume; what they give up, against a Grey, is the contextual precision and the sheer clarity. Judging an Amazon only on vocabulary misses the point — you'd be grading a singer on its diction.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">Why No Bird Is a Guaranteed Talker</h5>
    <p>Feathered exceptions break every rule. We've raised reserved Greys that whistle more than they speak, and Amazons that run silent or non-stop. Averages tell you the smart wager, never the outcome for one specific bird — which is why we place a companion rather than a promised performer, and say so plainly. No honest breeder of either bird will hand you a talking guarantee.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: Alex, Pepperberg and the Britannica record</h6>
    <p>The record backs it: <a href="https://www.britannica.com/animal/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Encyclopaedia Britannica ↗</a> describes the African Grey as "unsurpassed as a talker," and Pepperberg's thirty years with Alex are still the reference study in parrot cognition.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S12 NOISE & APARTMENT -->
  <section id="noise">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Louder All Day: Can an Amazon Share Your Walls?</h2>
    <p>More parrots lose their homes to noise than to cost, so anyone in an apartment should linger here. <strong>Quick answer: the African Grey is the quieter, more apartment-plausible bird; the Amazon is louder and projects all day.</strong></p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/parrot-noise-level-apartment-meter.webp" srcset="/parrot-noise-level-apartment-meter-760.webp 760w, /parrot-noise-level-apartment-meter.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Quietest parrot for an apartment: a noise meter placing the African Grey in the moderate band and the loud Amazon species toward the high end" loading="lazy">
    <p>On the parrot volume scale the Grey lands mid-band: whistles, chatter, a mimicked appliance or two, concentrated into fairly reliable morning and evening sessions. Owners describe Greys as among "the least 'screamy' parrots." Amazons run louder and, crucially, more <em>all-day</em>: two separate Reddit threads on "Amazon Parrot Noise Level (Apartment or Not)" exist for a reason. We won't invent a decibel figure — the ones floating around comparison articles are fabricated — but the direction is not in doubt: through shared walls, the Grey is the safer bet.</p>

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Is Any Amazon Quiet Enough for Neighbours?</h3>
    <p>If your heart is set on an Amazon but you have neighbors, the smaller species — a White-Fronted, for instance — are the least overwhelming, while the yellow-headed singers are the loudest. None of them is quieter than a Grey. There is no silent Amazon; there is only "less carrying," and the small species are where that road ends. For thin walls, the Grey wins this round, with dust — not noise — as its own trade-off.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S13 DUST & ALLERGIES -->
  <section id="dust">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Dust &amp; Dander: the African Grey Question for Allergy Homes</h2>
    <p>Here the comparison flips. Against a cockatoo, both birds are dusty; against an Amazon, <strong>the Grey is decisively the dustier one.</strong> African Greys are heavy powder-down birds, producing a fine feather dust that settles on shelves and stays airborne. Amazons are South American parrots and produce noticeably less. If someone in your home has asthma or bird allergies, this single section may decide the whole choice — and it's the one comparison article that Google currently sources to an unverified Facebook comment.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-dust-dander-air-purifier.webp" srcset="/african-grey-dust-dander-air-purifier-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-dust-dander-air-purifier.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="African grey dust and dander for allergy households: a Grey releases powder-down while a HEPA air purifier pulls the fine particles from the room" loading="lazy">
    <p>Owners of both are blunt about it. On the r/AfricanGrey cross-post, one keeper wrote "the f'n dust. Jesus. It never ends," and another that a HEPA filter came out "absolutely caked with feather dander." Per <a href="https://www.parrots.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">avian welfare educators ↗</a>, African and Australasian parrots are the dustiest groups while South American parrots (the Amazons) produce less. So if allergies are the constraint, the honest steer for once points at the Amazon — and away from our own bird.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">What Is Bird Fancier's Lung?</h3>
    <p>Bird Fancier's Lung is a hypersensitivity pneumonitis — an allergic lung inflammation some people develop after prolonged exposure to feather dust and droppings. It is uncommon, but it is real, and powder-down species like the Grey carry more of the dust that can trigger it. This is not a reason to fear a Grey; it is a reason to be honest with yourself about your household's lungs before committing to a four-to-six-decade dust source.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Can You Own a Grey With Asthma or Allergies?</h4>
    <p>Often yes — with management, and eyes open. Frequent misting or bathing tamps the powder down, a HEPA purifier beside the cage catches what floats, and wipeable surfaces mop up the remainder. But if a Grey's dust is a genuine medical problem in your home, an Amazon is the lower-dust bird, and we'd rather tell you that than sell you a Grey you can't breathe around.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Our Dust Verdict After a Decade of Greys</h5>
    <p>If asthma or bird allergies run in the family, sit with an adult Grey for an afternoon before deciding, and factor a purifier into the budget if the Grey wins. We'd rather lose a sale than place a dusty powder-down bird in a home that can't breathe with it — an Amazon may simply be the kinder fit.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: a documented grey-parrot lung case</h6>
    <p>It's documented, not theoretical: a peer-reviewed report in the <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9381342/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">U.S. National Library of Medicine ↗</a> traced an owner's hypersensitivity pneumonitis to their African Grey's feather dust. Powder-down dander is a real respiratory variable, and it's the Grey's, more than the Amazon's.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S14 READING A BITE -->
  <section id="bite">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Reading a Bite: Telegraphed vs Unsignalled</h2>
    <p>Sooner or later a serious buyer asks the awkward part out loud: how badly can it hurt me, and will there be a warning? Bite <em>force</em> is comparable between these two — both are strong-beaked mid-sized parrots. The real difference, and the thing no article states as behaviour, is bite <strong>style</strong>: a Grey tends to bite straight-on and telegraphs it; an Amazon is more likely to redirect, and its bite "twists."</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/parrot-body-language-bite-warning-diagram.webp" srcset="/parrot-body-language-bite-warning-diagram-760.webp 760w, /parrot-body-language-bite-warning-diagram.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Parrot body-language diagram: how an African Grey telegraphs a bite straight-on versus an Amazon's harder-to-read, redirected bite-and-twist" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">How an African Grey Telegraphs a Bite</h3>
    <p>A Grey usually warns you. Eye-pinning (the iris flashing), a raised nape, a stiff lean-away — the cues arrive before the beak does, and a Grey's bite tends to land straight-on. Owners describe it exactly that way: "a grey will bite you straight on." Respect the warning and most Grey bites never happen. When one does, it hurts and can draw blood, but it heals; a once-a-year event for a well-read bird, usually tied to something obvious like a vacuum near the cage.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why an Amazon's Bite Is Harder to Predict</h3>
    <p>An Amazon is the trickier read, especially in hormonal season. Owners warn that "Amazons tend to redirect their bites on the closest person or thing," and that an Amazon bites "and twists, making it comparatively a more painful bite." One keeper described a scar earned simply because the bird "didn't like the new house plant." None of this makes an Amazon dangerous by default — it makes body-language literacy non-negotiable, and it's why families with young kids should weigh the hormonal section next.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S15 HEALTH RISKS BY SPECIES -->
  <section id="health">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Health Risks by Species: What Actually Threatens Each Bird</h2>
    <p>Every parrot has a species-appropriate weak spot, and knowing your bird's is half of good ownership. The Grey's risks and the Amazon's are genuinely different animals — one leans metabolic and viral, the other dietary and hormonal — so a single "which is healthier?" answer misleads. Here's the honest, ledger-bounded map, with the external authorities clustered where a claim needs one.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-amazon-health-risk-silhouettes.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-amazon-health-risk-silhouettes-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-amazon-health-risk-silhouettes.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Health risks by species: an African Grey silhouette pinned with hypocalcemia and plucking, an Amazon silhouette pinned with obesity, fatty liver and hormonal aggression" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Health Conditions to Watch in African Greys</h3>
    <p>Greys carry two well-documented risks. Hypocalcemia — low blood calcium — is a grey-specific hazard the <a href="https://lafeber.com/vet/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lafeber veterinary resources ↗</a> flag clearly, held off with pellets, calcium-dense greens and daily UV-B light. The second is feather-destructive behavior, an enrichment problem more than a medical one. Both are why every C.A.Gs Grey ships with PBFD and Avian Polyomavirus PCR results and a written diet-and-lighting plan.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Why Hypocalcemia Hits Greys Hardest</h4>
    <p>Greys metabolise calcium unusually, so a diet that suits another parrot can leave a Grey deficient — presenting as weakness or, at worst, seizures.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">Calcium, Vitamin D3 and UV-B in Practice</h5>
    <p>The remedy is dull but reliable: enough dietary calcium alongside UV-B light, so the bird makes the Vitamin D3 it needs to put that calcium to use. Full-spectrum lighting is in our care notes from day one for exactly this reason.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Sourced to VCA / AAV avian guidance</h6>
    <p>The <a href="https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/african-grey-parrots-general" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VCA Animal Hospitals grey-parrot guide ↗</a> and the <a href="https://www.aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Association of Avian Veterinarians ↗</a> both cover the calcium/Vitamin-A picture; every buyer gets our specific plan on paper.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Health Conditions to Watch in Amazon Parrots</h3>
    <p>Amazons trade the Grey's calcium worry for two of their own: obesity with fatty liver disease, and hormonal aggression in the yellow-headed species. Both are managed — diet and exercise for the first, routine and realistic expectations for the second — but they're the Amazon's real long-term risks, and they're why we flag the yellow-heads as experienced-keeper birds.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Obesity and Fatty Liver Disease in Amazons</h4>
    <p>Amazons gain weight readily, and a seed-heavy bowl plus a quiet cage is the classic road to fatty liver disease — the Amazon's most preventable serious illness.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Diet-and-Exercise Warning</h5>
    <p>A pellet-forward diet, measured portions and real out-of-cage flight time keep an Amazon lean. It's the mirror of the Grey's calcium plan: a species-specific husbandry habit that quietly prevents the big bill.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Sourced to Lafeber nutrition guidance</h6>
    <p>The <a href="https://lafeber.com/pet-birds/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lafeber companion-bird nutrition library ↗</a> covers Amazon obesity and the pellet-versus-seed question in plain terms; the Vitamin-A deficiency both genera share is covered there too.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S16 SCORECARD — Gemini scorecard image + real data table kept in DOM for AIO -->
  <section id="scorecard">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Grey vs Amazon: Our Seven-Trait Scorecard</h2>
    <p>Arrived on a "which is better, African Grey or Amazon" search? Here it is as figures. We set every 0-to-10 mark ourselves, out of raising Greys and comparing notes with Amazon owners — considered judgment, not laboratory readings — and, because we don't sell Amazons, the scorecard isn't quietly rooting for a sale the way a seller's would.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-vs-amazon-decision-scorecard.webp" srcset="/african-grey-vs-amazon-decision-scorecard-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-vs-amazon-decision-scorecard.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Decision scorecard rating the African Grey and Amazon parrot from zero to ten on talking, singing, quietness, low dust, steady temperament, beginner fit and apartment fit" loading="lazy">
    <div class="tbl-wrap plain"><table class="score-tbl">
      <thead><tr><th>Trait</th><th>African Grey</th><th>Amazon</th><th>Our note</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>{scores.map((s) => (<tr><td class="sc-trait" data-label="Trait">{s.trait}</td><td class="sc" data-label="African Grey">{s.c}</td><td class="sc" data-label="Amazon">{s.t}</td><td class="sc-note" data-label="Our note">{s.note}</td></tr>))}</tbody>
    </table></div>
    <p>Read the pattern, not the totals: the Grey owns talking, quiet, low-hormonal steadiness and apartment fit; the Amazon owns singing and low dust outright. Neither column is a bad bird — you're choosing between a contextual talker and an extroverted singer.</p>
  </section>

