  <!-- S16 WHICH FITS YOUR HOUSEHOLD -->
  <section id="household">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Grey or Amazon: Which Suits Your Household?</h2>
    <p>Scores are useful; households are specific. Whether you're after the quietest parrot for apartment life, a bird that greets a busy family, or a low-dust companion for an allergy-prone home, the fit really comes down to who's home during the day, how much sound your walls forgive, and whether you'd rather converse with your bird or listen to it perform. Locate your circumstances below — it mirrors the rundown we send by email, and the point where a Reddit veteran's line applies: "you'll be ready when you can list the reasons you prefer one over the other."</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Match Your Household to the Bird</h3>
    <p>Five real household situations, five candid verdicts — one of them being "maybe wait a year."</p>
    <div class="match-grid">
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">For a First Parrot</h4><p>Lean African Grey, with eyes open — it's the steadier of the two in behaviour. Neither is a true beginner bird, but a big yellow-headed Amazon's hormonal swings and volume overwhelm most first-timers. If an Amazon is the dream, a smaller, calmer species and heavy research is the safer entry.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">For Families With Young Children</h4><p>Lean African Grey, on temperament and predictability. A hormonal yellow-head Amazon can redirect a bite onto the nearest person, and its bite "twists." Keep either bird supervised and at a distance from toddlers; this is a multi-decade responsibility, not a first pet.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">For Apartments and Condos</h4><p>African Grey, clearly — the quieter bird through shared walls. An Amazon projects all day, and the big singers carry. The Grey's trade-off here is dust, not noise, so pair the choice with an air purifier. Both need daily out-of-cage time regardless of square footage.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">Allergy-Prone Households</h4><p>This is the Amazon's column. Greys are heavy powder-down birds; Amazons produce far less dust. If asthma or bird allergies are in the home, the lower-dust Amazon is the kinder fit — one of the few rows where the honest steer points away from our own bird.</p></div>
      <div class="match-c"><h4 class="cag-h4">For Long-Workday Households</h4><p>Think hard, then think again — for either bird. Leave any parrot solo for ten-hour stretches and you invite plucking in a Grey and screaming in an Amazon. If your days are genuinely packed, waiting a year may beat buying this one.</p></div>
    </div>
    <p>Still undecided? Good — that's our favourite conversation. The form at the bottom reaches Mark and Teri directly, and "Grey or Amazon for a home like ours?" is a message we love answering.</p>
  </section>

