  <!-- S17 COST -->
  <section id="cost">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Does the First Year Actually Cost?</h2>
    <p>Almost no comparison prices out year one — so here it is, plainly. Our papered Congo Greys sit at $1,700–$3,500 and Timnehs at $1,500–$1,600, with a $200 deposit reserving a bird. Amazon prices vary widely by species and are set by other sellers, not us — we raise Greys only, so we won't quote an Amazon figure as if it were ours. Live per-bird figures, updated as each clutch weans, live on the <a href="/african-grey-parrot-price/">African Grey price guide</a>.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-first-year-cost-breakdown.webp" srcset="/african-grey-first-year-cost-breakdown-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-first-year-cost-breakdown.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="African grey vs amazon parrot price and first-year cost breakdown: bird, cage, avian vet, food and enrichment, with $185 airport and $350 home shipping" loading="lazy">

    <h3 class="cag-h3">Why the Purchase Price Is the Cheapest Part</h3>
    <p>For either bird, the sticker is a rounding error next to forty-plus years of food, avian-vet bills, toys and caging ahead. The trap sits at the cheap end of both markets: the "bargain" ads with no CITES paperwork, no sexing certificate and no vet check are the ones behind the fraud reports, and they're the listings buyers most often forward for us to inspect. A documented bird carries its price because the documentation is real work; an undocumented one isn't cheaper, it's a fundamentally different and riskier thing to buy.</p>

    <h4 class="cag-h4">What a C.A.Gs Grey's Price Already Covers</h4>
    <p>One price covers the whole trust stack, nothing tacked on afterward: captive-bred CITES papers, DNA sexing certificate, an avian vet's health certificate, a hatch record carrying the closed-band number, and PBFD and Polyomavirus PCR results. The only add-on is delivery — $185 to your nearest airport or $350 to your front door.</p>

    <h5 class="cag-h5">First-Year Costs After Your Grey Lands</h5>
    <p>Set aside roughly $825 to $2,000 in year one on top of the bird: a properly large cage ($300–$800), first perches and toys ($100–$300), an initial wellness exam ($75–$200 — find certified avian vets by area via the <a href="https://www.aav.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Association of Avian Veterinarians ↗</a>), a year of quality pellets ($200–$400), and a rotating toy budget ($150–$300). After year one, plan on roughly $375 to $1,350 annually — and note that an Amazon's obesity risk makes the pellet-and-vegetable line non-negotiable, not optional.</p>

    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: why we place only fully weaned birds</h6>
    <p>The internet is full of cut-price unweaned chicks, Grey and Amazon both. We refuse to sell one at any figure: mishandled hand-feeding — crop burns, aspiration — kills babies in inexperienced hands, and "finish weaning it yourself and save" is the worst bet in the whole hobby. Each bird leaves us fully weaned, and that work is already priced in.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S18 HORMONAL-MATURITY TIMELINE -->
  <section id="hormonal">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">The Hormonal-Maturity Timeline Nobody Warns You About</h2>
    <p>This is the section forums talk about and articles skip — and it's the thing that actually ends more Amazon ownerships than noise or cost. Both birds change as they mature, but the shape of that change is different, and it's the sharpest reason the "sweet baby" you meet is not the whole story. One breeder's line captures it: an Amazon is often harder at six years than six months, while a Grey trends the other way.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/amazon-vs-grey-hormonal-maturity-timeline.webp" srcset="/amazon-vs-grey-hormonal-maturity-timeline-760.webp 760w, /amazon-vs-grey-hormonal-maturity-timeline.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Hormonal-maturity timeline comparing an Amazon's sharp hormonal surge in its middle years against the African Grey's steadier, plucking-prone curve" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">How Each Bird Changes From Baby to Adult</h3>
    <p>Save this — it's what separates "my bird turned on me" from "my bird grew up on schedule."</p>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">1</span><b>0–1 yr · The Sweet Baby</b><p>Both a hand-raised Grey and a young Amazon are gentle, cuddly and easy at this age. This is the bird everyone meets — and the reason people underestimate the years ahead.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">2</span><b>2–4 yr · Personality Sets</b><p>The Grey settles into its watchful, one-person self and, if bored, may start plucking. The Amazon grows confident and "spicy," and the yellow-heads begin flexing the volume and attitude they're known for.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">3</span><b>4–6 yr · The Amazon Surge</b><p>Sexual maturity hits the yellow-headed Amazons hardest — seasonal aggression, divebombing, unpredictable bites. This is the window that fills rescues with Amazons whose owners weren't warned.</p></div>
      <div class="tl-c"><span class="tl-n">4</span><b>Lifelong · The Steadier Grey</b><p>A Grey's hormonal season is milder; its lifelong risk is boredom-driven plucking, not aggression. Enrichment and routine manage it. Neither bird is "fixed" — both are managed, in different directions.</p></div>
    </div>
    <p>None of this makes an Amazon a bad bird — it makes it a bird you buy with the six-year-old in mind, not just the six-month-old. It's also why our whole model is built around Greys: the steadier maturity curve suits the one-person, hand-raised companion we place.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S19 MYTHS -->
  <section id="myths">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Grey-and-Amazon Myths a Breeder Corrects</h2>
    <p>This niche repeats a handful of confident claims that simply aren't true, and buyers arrive quoting them. We won't name-and-shame the pages that print them; we'll just correct the claim against real birds. Reliable guides such as <a href="https://www.thesprucepets.com/the-smartest-pet-birds-4178388" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Spruce Pets' smartest-birds overview ↗</a> keep to what can be checked — so here's where the folklore diverges from the birds.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-amazon-myth-vs-reality-cards.webp" srcset="/african-grey-amazon-myth-vs-reality-cards-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-amazon-myth-vs-reality-cards.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Myth versus reality cards correcting claims about African Grey weight, a fictional black belly band, and whether an Amazon is the better first bird" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Myths Landing in Our Inbox</h3>
    <p>Two fast ones, then the anatomy whopper that earns its own reality check.</p>
    <div class="myth-grid">
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"An African Grey weighs about 2½ pounds."</strong> A figure that circulates online, and it's roughly double reality. A Congo African Grey is <strong>400–600 grams</strong> and most pet Amazons 300–700 grams — comparable, mid-sized birds, sourced to our own weights and Lafeber/VCA, not the inflated numbers some listings repeat.</p></div>
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"The Amazon is the better first bird."</strong> Repeated often, and shaky. A big yellow-headed Amazon's hormonal swings make it harder for a first-timer than a steadier Grey — the weight of attributed owner consensus, not our sales pitch, points the other way.</p></div>
    </div>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">The Big One: "African Greys Have a Black Belly Band"</h4>
    <p>A claim you'll actually find in circulation — and it's simply wrong.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">How to Really Tell the Two Apart</h5>
    <p>No, African Greys don't have a black belly band. The real field marks are a silver-grey body with fine scalloping, a bright red tail (maroon on the Timneh), a bare white face mask, a dark beak, and an iris that yellows with maturity. Amazons are green with species-specific head colour — red lores, a yellow nape, a blue front. If a page invents a "black band," it's describing a bird that doesn't exist.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: field marks per World Parrot Trust and our own birds</h6>
    <p>The corrected marks match the <a href="https://www.parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">World Parrot Trust grey-parrot profile ↗</a> and what we see in every clutch — red vs maroon tail, grey scalloping, the maturing iris — none of which involves a belly band.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S20 SHOULD YOU BUY EITHER AT ALL -->
  <section id="buy-either">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Should You Buy Either Bird At All?</h2>
    <p>Here's the section a seller isn't supposed to write. The forums say it constantly and no article will: for a lot of people, the honest answer to "Grey or Amazon?" is <strong>neither, or not yet.</strong> A veteran on the r/parrots comparison thread put the bar plainly — "you'll be ready when you can list the reasons you prefer one over the other." If you can't yet, that's not a failure; it's useful information, and we'd rather you find it here than a year into a rehoming.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Buy Neither If…</h3>
    <p>Buy neither, this year, if you're chasing a talking bird as a novelty — the ones who want "a talking bird" and little else are exactly who fills rescues. Buy neither if you work ten-hour days with no one home, if thin walls and a strict lease can't absorb any noise, or if a four-to-seven-decade commitment doesn't fit a life still in flux. A cockatiel or a budgie is a genuinely better first parrot, and saying so costs us a sale we didn't want to make.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">And No Bird Is a Guaranteed Talker</h4>
    <p>We'll state it plainly because no one else here does: we sell a companion, not a talking product. A Grey is the safest bet for contextual speech and an Amazon for song, but talking is a possibility, never a promise, and a bird bought purely to perform is a bird set up to disappoint. If the conversation is the <em>only</em> reason you want one, reconsider.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Planning for a Bird That May Outlive You</h3>
    <p>Both birds can outlive their owners — a Grey lives 40–60 years, an Amazon 40–70 — which is why rehoming is so common: not bad birds, but birds that outlast jobs, marriages and health. Either way, responsibility means a written succession plan: a named future caretaker who has actually met the bird, all its documents in a single folder, and a small fund set aside for the handover. Do that, and you've cleared the highest bar of responsible ownership before you've chosen a species at all.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S21 CITES -->
  <section id="cites">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Are African Greys and Amazons Wild-Caught? The CITES Answer</h2>
    <p>This is the question no comparison page in this niche answers — and one page in the field gets it backwards, hinting an African Grey is fine "if not wild-caught," which quietly implies wild-caught birds are on the table. They are not, from anyone reputable. The African Grey carries the treaty's top protection, CITES Appendix I, a status granted in 2017 after wild trapping had hollowed out native populations — history <a href="https://www.britannica.com/animal/grey-parrot" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Encyclopaedia Britannica ↗</a> sets out clearly. Plenty of Amazons are CITES-listed as well. None of this bans ownership — it simply makes documented captive-bred origin the whole ballgame.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-cites-captive-bred-passport.webp" srcset="/african-grey-cites-captive-bred-passport-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-cites-captive-bred-passport.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="CITES Appendix I captive-bred African Grey: a passport-style panel showing the bird is legal to own and transfer with full documentation, never wild-caught" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Document Folder Every Grey Travels With</h3>
    <p>Every Grey we send goes with its whole dossier — captive-bred CITES papers, a hatch record tied to the closed band number, a sexing certificate from the DNA lab and a health certificate from the avian vet. If any seller of any parrot — Grey, Amazon or otherwise — hesitates when you request those four, the hesitation is your answer.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What Appendix I Actually Means for a Buyer</h4>
    <p>The <a href="https://www.fws.gov/law/wild-bird-conservation-act" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wild Bird Conservation Act, laid out by the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service ↗</a>, is the barrier that keeps wild-trapped Appendix-I parrots out of US homes. Documented, home-bred birds change hands legally. Your Grey's band, meanwhile, was closed over its foot in the nest and can't be slipped onto a wild-caught adult afterward — which is why it counts for more than any sales receipt.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">What IUCN Status Means for Greys and Amazons</h5>
    <p>In their native ranges the Congo Grey is listed Endangered and the Timneh Vulnerable; of the Amazons on this page, the Yellow-Naped and Yellow-Shouldered face the gravest conservation concern. None of that clouds the legality of your captive-bred bird — but it's why we frame paperwork as ethics, not marketing. Every documented, home-bred placement removes one more market incentive to take a bird from the wild.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: CITES and IUCN Red List records</h6>
    <p>Listing sources: the <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES appendices database ↗</a> plus the <a href="https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22724813/154068024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IUCN Red List ↗</a> records for <em>Psittacus erithacus</em>, <em>Psittacus timneh</em> and the <em>Amazona</em> species named above.</p>
